    "explanation": "'vi' is the standard Unix visual editor, required by POSIX and present on essentially every Unix system. emacs is widely used but is an add-on rather than a standard component, and 'cat' only displays files, it cannot edit them."
  },
  {
    "id": "koc2012-q006",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "operating-systems",
    "subtopic": "unix-editors",
    "stem": "What are the two modes of the \"vi\" editor in Unix?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Insert and Delete",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Edit and Insert",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Delete and Edit",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "None of the above",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KOC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2012,
      "originalNumber": 6
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "ee94b7e5d45edd7d16848fb51c0690f48790dce8",
    "explanation": "vi has two modes: command mode (which this exam calls 'edit' mode, where keystrokes are interpreted as commands) and insert mode (where keystrokes become text). You press 'i' to enter insert mode and Esc to return to command mode. Deleting is not a mode, it is a command ('dd', 'x') issued from command mode, which rules out A and C."
  },
  {
    "id": "koc2012-q007",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "number-systems",
    "subtopic": "binary-to-decimal",
    "stem": "The decimal conversion of binary 1110 is:",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "2",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "15",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "8",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "14",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KOC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2012,
      "originalNumber": 7
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "6953517f9882af777285af53d6e499ce380591fe",
    "explanation": "Binary 1110 = 1*8 + 1*4 + 1*2 + 0*1 = 14. The classic slip is answering 15, which is 1111; the low bit here is 0, so subtract 1."
  },
  {
    "id": "koc2012-q008",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "number-systems",
    "subtopic": "decimal-to-binary",
    "stem": "The binary conversion of decimal 30 is:",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "11110",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "10110",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "10001",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "00111",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KOC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2012,
      "originalNumber": 8
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "637b886f29fa8ccc4866d8696abf4de49736a987",
    "explanation": "30 = 16 + 8 + 4 + 2, so bits 4,3,2,1 are set and bit 0 is clear, giving 11110. Check the distractor: 10110 = 16 + 4 + 2 = 22, not 30."
  },
